    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA90-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi talaimakaṭku (EN: talaimakaḷukku) uraippāḷāyp pāṇaṉai neruṅki vāyiṉ maṟuttatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante as one who is talking to HER refused the door to the bard.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA90">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            āṭiyal viḻavi ṉaḻuṅkaṉ mūtū</l>
<l>            ruṭaiyōr paṉmaiyiṟ peruṅkai tūvā</l>
<l>            vaṟaṉil pulaitti yellit tōytta</l>
<l>            pukarppukark koṇṭa puṉpūṅ kaliṅkamoṭu</l>
<l>            vāṭā mālai tuyalvara vōṭip </l>
<l>            peruṅkayiṟu nālu mirumpaṉam piṇaiyaṟ</l>
<l>            pūṅka ṇāya muyaṅka vūṅkā</l>
<l>            ḷaḻutaṉaḷ peyaru mañci lōti</l>
<l>            nalkūr peṇṭiṉ cilvaḷaik kuṟumaka</l>
<l>            ḷūca luṟutoḻiṟ pūcaṟ kūṭṭā </l>
<l>            nayaṉiṉ mākkaḷoṭu kuḻīip</l>
<l>            payaṉiṉ ṟammaviv vēntuṭai yavaiyē.</l>
        </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Of no avail, alas, is this assembly with a king,<note place="foot">Here we have another interesting cases where T.V.G. does not accept the poem at face value as a description of a festival meant to provide opportunity for the sexes to meet, but in accordance with the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term> about HER anger against HIM, preventing her even to swing with her companions.</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">crowded with people without longing,</l>
<l rend="indent">since the small daughter with few bangles of a poor woman</l>
<l rend="indent">does not join<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kūṭṭā</term> must be read here with <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟumakaḷ</term> as subject. Actually we expect the intransitive form (<term xml:lang="ta">kūṭā</term>).</note> in the bustle of activity on the swings,</l>
<l rend="indent2">[she with] pretty thin hair who comes back crying<note place="foot">Here once more this strange construction of a seemingly finite verb + <term xml:lang="ta">peyareccam</term>, a particular form of <term xml:lang="ta">muṟṟeccam</term>, perhaps used to clarify the temporal order of events (cf. NA 370.9 <term xml:lang="ta">uḷḷiṉeṉ uṟaiyum</term>; NA 399.8 <term xml:lang="ta">nayantaṉaṉ varūum</term>).</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">not swinging, while [her] flower-eyed companions embrace each other</l>
<l rend="indent">on the fusion of big palmyra leaves that is hanging on big ropes,</l>
<l rend="indent2">as the dutiless washerwoman runs, so that [her] unfaded garland</l>
<l rend="indent3">comes into swinging, with the cloth with red(?) flowers</l>
<l rend="indent4">that had absorbed the paste(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pukarpukar</term> is explained by T.V.G. as the rice-gruel used by the washerwoman to starch the clothes.</note>, soaked over night,</l>
<l>[her] big hands not resting in the multitude, examining the dresses,</l>
<l rend="indent3">in the noisy old village in dance festival.</l>
        </lg>
